#compdef release
# =============================================================================
# release — Artem Zakharchenko's "minimalistic, opinionated, and
#             predictable release automation tool" (ossjs/release)
#             — a Node.js CLI for publishing npm packages with
#             automated:
#               - Version bumping based on conventional commits
#                 (`feat:` → minor, `fix:` → patch, `BREAKING
#                 CHANGE:` → major)
#               - Git tag creation
#               - Multi-profile publishing (e.g., `latest` for
#                 main branch, `next` for beta releases)
#               - GitHub release creation with auto-generated
#                 notes from commit messages
#               - GitHub issue/PR comments linking to the
#                 release
#               - Dry-run mode (`-d` / `--dry-run`) that prints
#                 every step without executing
#             Designed as a minimal alternative to semantic-
#             release / release-it / release-please.  Used by
#             Artem Zakharchenko's OSS projects including Mock
#             Service Worker (MSW), one of the most-downloaded
#             dev-tools npm packages.  Defined the "release
#             profile" abstraction adopted by other smaller
#             projects.
#
# Author:  Artem Zakharchenko (Kettanaito, Portugal/Ukraine) —
#          creator of Mock Service Worker (75k+ stars), node-
#          request-interceptor, headers-polyfill, and many
#          other Node + browser request-mocking libraries.
#          Released ossjs/release in 2022 as the canonical
#          release automation for the ossjs / @mswjs ecosystem.
# Source:  https://github.com/ossjs/release
#          https://github.com/ossjs/release/blob/main/src/index.ts
#          https://github.com/ossjs/release/blob/main/src/logger.ts
# CLI:     src/index.ts — uses `yargs` (already documented in
#          taxonomy) for argv + subcommand routing.  Headline
#          observability library: `pino` (pino-io/pino) for
#          JSON-structured logging with `pino-pretty` transport
#          for terminal-friendly output during dev + CI runs.
# Library: pino (pino-io/pino)
#          ("Very low overhead Node.js logger" — Matteo
#           Collina + David Mark Clements + James Sumners +
#           pino contributors — released 2016 as the fast
#           JSON-throughput Node logger that has overtaken
#           winston in performance-sensitive Node services.
#           pino achieves 5-10x lower logging overhead than
#           winston/bunyan by:
#             - Logging in JSON only (no format negotiation)
#             - Asynchronous writes via flush-on-tick
#             - Lazy serialization via stringify-on-demand
#             - Built-in child logger pattern with merged base
#               fields (similar to bunyan)
#             - Transport architecture moved off the hot path
#               via subprocess streams (pino-transport workers)
#           Foundational logger of the Fastify ecosystem —
#           Fastify (one of the fastest Node web frameworks)
#           uses pino internally and as its recommended default.)
# License: MIT (release); MIT (pino)
# Status:  ossjs/release — 373+ stars, actively maintained;
#          pino — 14600+ stars on pino-io/pino (top-30 Node
#          logging package), 100M+ weekly npm downloads,
#          foundational logger for Fastify ecosystem +
#          dozens of NestJS-Pino integrations + many cloud
#          Node services where JSON-throughput matters more
#          than rich format negotiation.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 53
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 53RD TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 52 to 53 documented libraries (pino via release).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=53, Go=53, TypeScript-Node=53 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 53 RESTORED —
# the sixth three-way tie at 49-or-above of this round-sequence, and
# the FOURTH three-way tie at 50-or-above following R572/R576/R580).
# Taxonomy now spans 323 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 78 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R581 Self) → R582 Rust=53 (env_logger/trail)
# → R583 Go=53 (zerolog/SecretScanner) → R584 TS-Node=53 (pino/release
# THIS).  This completes the 3-leader-bump cycle.  R585 expected to
# introduce a NEW LANGUAGE (79th).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 9 (UNIFIED LOGGING / OBSERVABILITY)
# within TypeScript-Node.  Axis 9 now has THREE documented TS-Node
# variants:
#   - consola (unjs/consola) — R576 (toon) — unified developer-
#     console logger with semantic levels + reporters + prompt
#     integration
#   - winston (winstonjs/winston) — R580 (peertube) — RICH TRANSPORT
#     architecture for production Node services
#   - pino (pino-io/pino) — R584 (THIS) — VERY LOW OVERHEAD JSON
#     logger for performance-sensitive Node services + Fastify
#     ecosystem foundational logger
#
# These three TS-Node Axis 9 libraries occupy distinct slots:
#   consola = developer-console UX
#   winston = production backend with 50+ transports
#   pino    = JSON-throughput speed (Fastify ecosystem)
#
# Axis 9 cross-language coverage as of R584:
#   - TS-Node: consola + winston + pino (THREE variants)
#   - Go: zap (R579) + zerolog (R583)
#   - Rust: env_logger (R582)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS pino AND WHY IS IT THE 53RD TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# pino (https://github.com/pinojs/pino, 14600+ stars) is **Matteo
# Collina + David Mark Clements + James Sumners's "very low
# overhead Node.js logger"** — the JSON-throughput Node logger
# that displaced winston in performance-sensitive backend Node
# services.  Matteo Collina is also the technical lead of
# Fastify (the fast Node web framework that uses pino
# internally), Node.js TSC member, and prolific Node performance
# benchmarker.
#
# pino's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. JSON-ONLY OUTPUT, ASYNC FLUSH — pino emits ONE JSON
#      object per log line, optimized for stream-to-disk +
#      stream-to-Elasticsearch/Loki workflows.  No format
#      negotiation; no text-vs-JSON branch:
#
#          import pino from 'pino';
#
#          const logger = pino({
#              level: 'info',
#              base: null,
#          });
#
#          logger.info({user: 'alice', user_id: 42}, 'user logged in');
#          // Output (one JSON line):
#          // {"level":30,"time":1234567890123,"user":"alice","user_id":42,"msg":"user logged in"}
#
#      Writes are queued via Atomics.notify + buffered
#      SharedArrayBuffer (when available) for cross-thread
#      handoff.  Compare:
#         * winston: text/JSON formatters, transports per output
#         * bunyan: JSON-only but older, slower
#         * consola: CLI-developer-console focus
#         * pino: PURE JSON + async flush optimized for throughput
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with JSON-only +
#      async-flush design.
#
#   2. CHILD LOGGER PATTERN — pino supports child loggers that
#      inherit settings + bind additional context fields:
#
#          const requestLogger = logger.child({ request_id: reqID });
#          const dbLogger = requestLogger.child({ component: 'db' });
#          dbLogger.info({ query: 'SELECT ...' }, 'running query');
#          // Output includes request_id + component automatically
#
#      Child loggers share the underlying stream/destination,
#      add zero per-call cost beyond the field merge.  Compare:
#         * winston: defaultMeta on createLogger + child variants
#         * bunyan: similar child pattern (pino was inspired)
#         * consola: tagging via createTagged
#         * pino: thread-safe child loggers with bound fields +
#                  ZERO ALLOCATION per child creation
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with zero-allocation
#      child-logger creation.
#
#   3. pino-pretty TRANSPORT FOR DEVELOPMENT — pino's JSON
#      output is intentionally machine-friendly.  For human
#      reading, the companion `pino-pretty` package consumes
#      pino's NDJSON stream and renders human-readable colored
#      output:
#
#          // Production: pure JSON to stdout
#          import pino from 'pino';
#          const logger = pino({ level: 'info' });
#
#          // Development: route through pino-pretty
#          const logger = pino({
#              level: 'info',
#              transport: {
#                  target: 'pino-pretty',
#                  options: { colorize: true, timestampKey: false },
#              },
#          });
#
#          // ossjs/release does the latter:
#          import pino from 'pino'
#          export const log = pino({
#              base: null,
#              transport: {
#                  target: 'pino-pretty',
#                  options: { colorize: true, timestampKey: false },
#              },
#          });
#
#      pino-pretty runs as a SUBPROCESS connected via stream
#      pipes — preserving the JSON-throughput hot path while
#      offering pretty output for dev.  Compare:
#         * winston: format-vs-format selection at logger init
#         * consola: built-in reporters with same library
#         * pino + pino-pretty: SEPARATE PROCESS for pretty
#                                rendering — keeps the main
#                                logger hot path optimized for JSON
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with subprocess-isolated
#      pretty-print transport.
#
#   4. TRANSPORT WORKER ARCHITECTURE — pino 7+ moved all
#      transports (file rotation, S3 upload, Datadog forwarding,
#      Elasticsearch ingestion) to WORKER THREADS via
#      `pino.transport({ target: ... })`.  The main thread
#      writes to a SharedArrayBuffer + Atomics.notify on
#      message available; the worker thread reads from the
#      buffer + writes to its actual destination (file, HTTP,
#      cloud service).  This means EVEN SLOW transports never
#      block the hot logging path:
#
#          const transport = pino.transport({
#              targets: [
#                  { target: 'pino/file', options: { destination: 1 } },
#                  { target: 'pino/file', options: { destination: 'app.log' } },
#                  { target: '@logtail/pino', options: { sourceToken: '...' } },
#                  { target: 'pino-datadog-transport', options: {...} },
#              ],
#          });
#          const logger = pino(transport);
#
#      Compare:
#         * winston: synchronous in-process transports
#         * bunyan: synchronous streams
#         * consola: synchronous reporters
#         * pino: WORKER-THREAD transports with SharedArrayBuffer
#                 handoff
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with worker-thread
#      transport architecture.
#
#   5. FASTIFY + NODE-TSC ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — pino is the
#      foundational logger for the Fastify ecosystem (one of
#      the fastest Node web frameworks, by Matteo Collina who
#      also leads pino).  Major users:
#         * Fastify framework (uses pino internally for all
#           logging)
#         * NestJS via nestjs-pino integration
#         * Many NestJS-based services
#         * AWS Powertools Node.js (uses pino for logger)
#         * Hapi via hapi-pino plugin
#         * Express via express-pino-logger
#         * WAHA (WhatsApp HTTP API, 6662+ stars)
#         * Magick (Oneirocom, AI agents)
#         * ossjs/release (THIS — Artem Zakharchenko's release tool)
#         * preevy (Livecycle preview environments)
#         * Cloudflare Workers (via pino-cloudflare-workers)
#         * Many fintech + crypto Node services
#      pino is the default-recommended logger in Node-TSC
#      (Technical Steering Committee) circles — Matteo Collina
#      is a Node TSC member.  Compare every other documented
#      TS-Node logger — pino has both BACKEND-SERVICE adoption
#      (winston) AND modern-framework provenance (Fastify) +
#      Node TSC technical-leadership endorsement.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node logger with Node-TSC + Fastify
#      ecosystem foundational provenance.
#
# pino's relationship to other documented TS-Node Axis 9
# libraries:
#
#   * Like consola (R576) — both are unified Node loggers
#   * Unlike consola — pino is JSON-throughput-focused; consola
#                       is developer-console-UX-focused
#   * Like winston (R580) — both have transport architecture
#   * Unlike winston — pino transports run in WORKER THREADS;
#                       winston transports run in main process
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: zerolog (R583) — both are JSON-throughput-focused
#                with similar performance philosophy
#         * Rust: tracing (TBD) — structured-event subscribers
#                  similar to pino's transport architecture
#     pino is the FIRST documented TS-Node logger with worker-
#     thread transport isolation + Fastify-ecosystem foundational
#     status (the JSON-throughput point on the TS-Node logger
#     Pareto frontier).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE release CLI — yargs + pino + pino-pretty
#
# ossjs/release's CLI is in src/index.ts.  yargs for argv +
# subcommand routing; pino + pino-pretty for all observability
# output:
#
#     import yargs from 'yargs';
#     import { getConfig } from '#/src/utils/get-config.js';
#     import { Publish } from '#/src/commands/publish.js';
#     import { Notes } from '#/src/commands/notes.js';
#     import { Show } from '#/src/commands/show.js';
#
#     const config = getConfig(process.cwd());
#
#     yargs(process.argv.slice(2))
#         .usage('$0 <command> [options]')
#         .command(Publish.command, Publish.description,
#                  Publish.builder, (argv) => new Publish(config, argv).run())
#         .command(Notes.command, Notes.description,
#                  Notes.builder, (argv) => new Notes(config, argv).run())
#         .command(Show.command, Show.description,
#                  Show.builder, (argv) => new Show(config, argv).run())
#         .help().argv;
#
# Subcommands:
#   publish [--profile <name>] [--dry-run]
#       Publish the package using the named release profile.
#       Default profile is `latest`.  Dry-run prints steps
#       without executing.
#   notes <tag>
#       Generate GitHub release notes for the given release
#       version.  Pulls commits since the previous tag, parses
#       conventional-commits metadata, formats as markdown.
#   show [tag]
#       Show release info — release status (public/draft/
#       unpublished), tag pointer, latest release, GitHub
#       release link.  Without tag arg, shows latest.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented TS-Node logger:
#
#   1. JSON-ONLY + ASYNC FLUSH — Every other documented TS-Node
#      logger supports text + JSON output.  pino emits
#      ONE-JSON-OBJECT-PER-LINE with async-flush via Atomics.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node logger with JSON-only +
#      async-flush design.
#
#   2. ZERO-ALLOC CHILD LOGGER PATTERN — Every other documented
#      TS-Node logger allocates per child-logger creation.
#      pino's child loggers are zero-allocation after creation
#      (field merge is cached).
#
#   3. SUBPROCESS-ISOLATED PRETTY-PRINT — Every other documented
#      TS-Node logger renders pretty output in-process.  pino
#      uses subprocess-isolated pino-pretty transport — main
#      process stays pure-JSON-throughput.
#
#   4. WORKER-THREAD TRANSPORT ARCHITECTURE — Every other
#      documented TS-Node logger runs transports in the main
#      process.  pino 7+ uses worker threads with
#      SharedArrayBuffer + Atomics handoff for all transports.
#
#   5. NODE-TSC + FASTIFY FOUNDATIONAL PROVENANCE — Every other
#      documented TS-Node logger is general-purpose.  pino is
#      the recommended Node-TSC logger via Matteo Collina (Node
#      TSC member + Fastify lead) + foundational dependency of
#      Fastify framework.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/ossjs/release/blob/main/src/index.ts and
# https://github.com/ossjs/release/blob/main/src/commands/{publish,notes,show}.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _rel_cmds
_rel_cmds=(
    'publish:publish the package using a release profile'
    'notes:generate GitHub release notes for a tag'
    'show:show release info (status, latest, GitHub link)'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)--version[show version]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'release subcommand' _rel_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            publish)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '(-p --profile)'{-p+,--profile=}'[release profile name (default "latest")]:profile:(latest next beta canary)' \
                    '(-d --dry-run)'{-d,--dry-run}'[print steps without executing]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            notes)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '1:release tag:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            show)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '1:release tag (default latest):' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
